I gave that back to the doc,

238
00:14:17,893 --> 00:14:19,763
same night I took it from him,

239
00:14:19,763 --> 00:14:22,090
same night we became friends.

240
00:14:22,090 --> 00:14:26,758
Recall where you were
when Grant was killed?

241
00:14:26,758 --> 00:14:29,488
Playing poker at Skinny's tavern.

242
00:14:29,488 --> 00:14:32,006
- Ask Skinny, he'll tell you.
- Will do.

243
00:14:32,006 --> 00:14:34,445
Besides, I never would have hurt the doc.

244
00:14:34,445 --> 00:14:36,240
He was my protege.

245
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:38,530
No offense, Cy, but...

246
00:14:38,530 --> 00:14:40,612
you don't seem like the mentor type.

247
00:14:40,612 --> 00:14:45,516
I tried to teach him the game,
but the guy...

248
00:14:45,516 --> 00:14:48,743
was torn between two lovers.

249
00:14:48,743 --> 00:14:59,954
Good evening.
Can you check this off?

250
00:14:59,954 --> 00:15:01,979
That's okay.

251
00:15:01,979 --> 00:15:04,444
- Here you can.
- Yes, of course.

252
00:15:04,444 --> 00:15:10,578
Well, a toast to Jason's
future alma mater, Cornell.

253
00:15:12,180 --> 00:15:15,385
I hear you've been shadowing
your dad in the ER, Jason?

254
00:15:15,385 --> 00:15:17,134
But he's surgeon material.

255
00:15:17,134 --> 00:15:20,014
I like the ER.
People need your help right away,

256
00:15:20,014 --> 00:15:22,551
- and then, you save them.
- And they're forever grateful.

257
00:15:22,551 --> 00:15:27,101
Like Mrs. Lee who brought another
angelfish for our aquarium today.

258
00:15:27,101 --> 00:15:30,210
'Cause that's how she thinks
of you as her angel.

259
00:15:30,210 --> 00:15:32,282
Oh, boy.

260
00:15:32,739 --> 00:15:36,013
- You sure?
- I'm afraid so.

261
00:15:36,013 --> 00:15:40,446
- What's wrong?
- Credit cards aren't working.

262
00:15:41,371 --> 00:15:43,975
I didn't bring my purse.

263
00:15:43,975 --> 00:15:47,131
Uh, I'll just have to write a check.

264
00:15:47,131 --> 00:15:48,751
I'm afraid we don't take checks.

265
00:15:48,751 --> 00:15:52,380
Well, you just might have 
to make an exception tonight.

266
00:15:52,380 --> 00:15:55,089
I'm sorry, sir.

267
00:16:00,028 --> 00:16:03,113
Uh, that's the ER.
Damn it. Uh...

268
00:16:03,113 --> 00:16:08,442
- Um, I'll take that check, waiter.
- No, no, we invited you.

269
00:16:08,442 --> 00:16:12,501
I'm so sorry, but...
I'm on call.

270
00:16:12,501 --> 00:16:16,136
- Sara's dad is not paying.
- No, he's not.

271
00:16:16,136 --> 00:16:21,142
We'll get to the bottom of this.
Please, order dessert.

272
00:16:26,979 --> 00:16:29,083
What is going on?

273
00:16:29,083 --> 00:16:31,645
I don't know.
It's a bank snafu.

274
00:16:31,645 --> 00:16:35,152
- It's really embarrassing.
- Anne, I have to run.

275
00:16:35,152 --> 00:16:37,090
You can't just walk out on 
your son's graduation dinner.

276
00:16:37,090 --> 00:16:40,005
It's work. / And stick his girlfriend's
parents with the bill.

277
00:16:40,005 --> 00:16:42,884
It's the hospital.
Look, I have to go.

278
00:16:42,884 --> 00:16:46,098
Why are you on call tonight, anyway?

279
00:16:47,514 --> 00:16:50,279
I'm sorry.

280
00:16:56,582 --> 00:17:00,347
It was the game or the lady.

281
00:17:00,347 --> 00:17:02,402
And the lady lost.

282
00:17:02,402 --> 00:17:05,283
You think she knew 
what the competition was?

283
00:17:05,283 --> 00:17:10,007
My experience?
Wives always know.

284
00:17:10,007 --> 00:17:12,485
I hear you.

285
00:17:13,627 --> 00:17:15,342
Did some checking, Anne.

286
00:17:15,342 --> 00:17:20,419
You got $1.5 million in life
insurance, after Grant died.

287
00:17:20,419 --> 00:17:22,673
Yes. So?

288
00:17:22,673 --> 00:17:24,901
Well, so it must have come in handy,

289
00:17:24,901 --> 00:17:27,372
considering you were broke.

290
00:17:27,372 --> 00:17:29,645
If you think I'm some
kind of black widow...

291
00:17:29,645 --> 00:17:31,505
I know there were money problems.

292
00:17:31,505 --> 00:17:34,358
Grant was screwing up your life,
humiliating you.

293
00:17:34,358 --> 00:17:36,085
He was in trouble.

294
00:17:36,085 --> 00:17:39,115
But you didn't mention that.

295
00:17:39,115 --> 00:17:40,736
What does that have to do 
with him dying?

296
00:17:40,736 --> 00:17:42,423
Maybe everything,

297
00:17:42,423 --> 00:17:45,862
because maybe you did 
something about it. / I tried.

298
00:17:45,862 --> 00:17:48,560
I tried to save him.

299
00:17:48,560 --> 00:17:52,011
- Any luck?
- None.

300
00:17:58,627 --> 00:18:00,931
What are you doing?

301
00:18:03,699 --> 00:18:06,638
Uh, just, uh...

302
00:18:06,638 --> 00:18:09,688
looking for a pen.

303
00:18:09,688 --> 00:18:12,163
You're trying to steal from me?

304
00:18:12,163 --> 00:18:16,604
- That's ridiculous.
- Yes, it is, but that's what you're doing.

305
00:18:16,604 --> 00:18:21,766
Cornell called today.
Tuition check bounced.

306
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:24,912
- Bank snafu.
- Another one? / Must be.

307
00:18:24,912 --> 00:18:28,965
Grant, you're a doctor. I'm a professor, 
and both our bank accounts are empty.

308
00:18:28,965 --> 00:18:34,336
- What the hell is happening?
- Okay, uh...

309
00:18:36,414 --> 00:18:38,640
I've been playing poker.

310
00:18:38,640 --> 00:18:40,170
You gambled away our money?

311
00:18:40,170 --> 00:18:43,430
- But I'm gonna win it back.
- Grant.

312
00:18:43,430 --> 00:18:45,594
When I'm at that table,

313
00:18:45,594 --> 00:18:47,844
it's like I'm playing with fate.

314
00:18:47,844 --> 00:18:50,602
It's dangerous and exhilarating.

315
00:18:50,602 --> 00:18:52,685
It sounds like you're talking about a drug.

316
00:18:52,685 --> 00:18:55,144
But you can't get good at a drug.

317
00:18:55,144 --> 00:18:56,940
Do you hear yourself?

318
00:18:56,940 --> 00:19:01,863
I'm getting good, really good.

319
00:19:06,466 --> 00:19:08,848
- That's the ER.
- No, it's not.

320
00:19:08,848 --> 00:19:11,102
It hasn't been the ER
in a long time, has it?

321
00:19:11,102 --> 00:19:15,912
- I'm gonna win it all back.
- Grant, stop. Before Jason finds out.

322
00:19:15,912 --> 00:19:17,854
Don't tell him.
It's just a temporary problem.

323
00:19:17,854 --> 00:19:20,195
He's gonna find out 
when we can't pay his tuition.

324
00:19:20,195 --> 00:19:22,280
Just trust me!

325
00:19:24,588 --> 00:19:28,031
We'd been married 18 years.

326
00:19:28,031 --> 00:19:34,600
And suddenly I didn't know him anymore.

327
00:19:36,430 --> 00:19:39,099
- Did your son find out?
- Yeah.

328
00:19:39,099 --> 00:19:41,562
'Cause we couldn't afford Cornell.

329
00:19:41,562 --> 00:19:44,377
That must have crushed him.

330
00:19:44,377 --> 00:19:49,476
He had to go to community college.
Work two jobs.

331
00:19:49,476 --> 00:19:51,543
It turned him against Grant forever.

332
00:19:51,543 --> 00:19:57,660
So when Grant died,
he and Jason were estranged.

333
00:19:57,660 --> 00:19:59,979
At least with the insurance money,

334
00:19:59,979 --> 00:20:03,962
Jason got to transfer
to Cornell the next year.

335
00:20:03,962 --> 00:20:06,681
He's a doctor now.

336
00:20:06,681 --> 00:20:11,173
Just like he always wanted.

337
00:20:14,176 --> 00:20:16,222
You know that witness, Edie?

338
00:20:16,222 --> 00:20:17,995
The ex-junkie?

339
00:20:17,995 --> 00:20:20,609
- She called me.
- And?

340
00:20:21,057 --> 00:20:23,436
That's it. Just saying.

341
00:20:23,436 --> 00:20:25,215
Saying what?

342
00:20:25,215 --> 00:20:29,365
Saying that maybe I'm not a 100%
totally washed up in the dating world.

343
00:20:29,365 --> 00:20:32,463
Because a crack-ho called you?

344
00:20:32,463 --> 00:20:34,662
Why you have to say it like that?

345
00:20:34,662 --> 00:20:37,191
I got something on Jason.
One of his two jobs?

346
00:20:37,191 --> 00:20:41,037
Was working at the blood
bank at st. Walter's. / That relevant?

347
00:20:41,037 --> 00:20:43,481
According to the web site,
each time you donate,

348
00:20:43,481 --> 00:20:46,520
you get juice, a cookie,
and a red, heart-shaped sticker.

349
00:20:46,520 --> 00:20:49,554
- Like the one at our crime scene.
- That's the trifecta right there.

350
00:20:49,554 --> 00:20:53,323
Knows the victim, associated
with the hospital, and that sticker.

351
00:20:53,323 --> 00:20:57,908
And a million and a half reasons
to see his dad dead.

352
00:21:32,868 --> 00:21:35,099
Which one's yours?

353
00:21:35,099 --> 00:21:38,992
Oh, none.

354
00:21:42,829 --> 00:21:46,466
- You like the boys or the girls?
- Excuse me?

355
00:21:46,466 --> 00:21:51,235
Seems like you're watching
the kid in blue pretty close.

356
00:21:51,235 --> 00:21:55,777
- Don't know what you mean.
- He's weak, no friends.

357
00:21:55,777 --> 00:21:58,306
- He's a good pick.
- I'm trying to read.

358
00:21:58,306 --> 00:22:01,368
You'd rather have the blonde kid.

359
00:22:02,485 --> 00:22:06,583
He's popular, athletic.
You move on him,

360
00:22:06,583 --> 00:22:09,833
he'll tell you to go pound sand.

361
00:22:11,547 --> 00:22:15,884
Guess you know something about it.

362
00:22:29,926 --> 00:22:32,651
I know what you are.

363
00:22:32,651 --> 00:22:35,514
I make a study out of people like you.

364
00:22:35,514 --> 00:22:40,180
I'm not doing anything.
You're thinking about it.

365
00:22:42,601 --> 00:22:45,631
No law against that.

366
00:22:46,385 --> 00:22:49,221
You're not gonna read here anymore.

367
00:22:49,221 --> 00:22:53,433
You're gonna walk away right now.
And if you come back,

368
00:22:53,433 --> 00:22:58,760
I'll find you,
and I'll wreck you.

369
00:23:14,613 --> 00:23:17,095
We have to talk, Jason.

370
00:23:18,029 --> 00:23:20,331
Who asked you to open
my dad's case again?

371
00:23:20,331 --> 00:23:21,837
We don't need a formal invite.

372
00:23:21,837 --> 00:23:25,049
I'm just wondering who the hell cares.
I know I don't.

373
00:23:25,049 --> 00:23:26,340
That's pretty tough.

374
00:23:26,340 --> 00:23:29,382
I have surgery in six minutes,
and I'm punctual, so...

375
00:23:29,382 --> 00:23:31,708
So where were you
when your dad was killed?

376
00:23:31,708 --> 00:23:34,256
- You're talking to me like a suspect.
- Picked up on that, huh?

377
00:23:34,256 --> 00:23:36,881
We're down to five minutes now.

378
00:23:36,881 --> 00:23:38,942
He embarrassed you
in front of your girlfriend,

379
00:23:38,942 --> 00:23:41,846
made you pull out of Cornell.
All 'cause of his gambling.

380
00:23:41,846 --> 00:23:44,454
I'm not denying he was a bum.

381
00:23:45,061 --> 00:23:47,312
Did you always think that?

382
00:23:47,312 --> 00:23:51,186
No. I used to worship him.

383
00:23:51,186 --> 00:23:54,522
I watched him raise people
from the dead.

384
00:23:54,522 --> 00:23:57,962
Can't see something like that
and not want to be just like the guy.

385
00:23:57,962 --> 00:24:01,518
- But then he let you down.
- Yeah, well...

386
00:24:01,518 --> 00:24:04,326
that's the way it goes.

387
00:24:04,326 --> 00:24:07,147
So that night?

388
00:24:07,147 --> 00:24:12,656
I was at a bar, Clancy's.
Got drunk, first, only time in my life.

389
00:24:12,656 --> 00:24:14,277
Why that of all nights?

390
00:24:14,277 --> 00:24:17,477
Because I'd just seen first-hand
what my dad had become.

391
00:24:17,477 --> 00:24:20,852
- A bum?
- And a menace.

392
00:24:21,178 --> 00:24:23,219
Dr. Bowen, my husband is back.

393
00:24:23,219 --> 00:24:26,556
Really? Sorry. / He's in the OR.
Will you check on him?

394
00:24:26,556 --> 00:24:30,397
- You're the only one...
- Can't just now, Mrs. Lee.

395
00:24:32,260 --> 00:24:37,530
Start a line.
2 million units of penicillin, 500 of gent.

396
00:24:37,530 --> 00:24:39,535
- Dad!
- Quiet, Jason.

397
00:24:39,535 --> 00:24:46,386
- But, dad, the chart...
- Jason, you watch, I work. Understand?

398
00:24:51,671 --> 00:24:53,851
Dr. Garvey!

399
00:24:54,420 --> 00:24:57,554
He's giving him penicillin.

400
00:24:58,963 --> 00:25:01,554
- Stop! He's pen allergic, Grant.
- What?

401
00:25:01,554 --> 00:25:03,431
Clindamycin.
And get Dr. Marsh.

402
00:25:03,431 --> 00:25:05,982
You, come with me.

403
00:25:12,284 --> 00:25:15,196
You could've sent him into 
anaphylactic shock. / I missed it, sorry.

404
00:25:15,196 --> 00:25:17,575
"Sorry" is for when you show up
to work a zombie.

405
00:25:17,575 --> 00:25:19,992
"Sorry" is for when you borrow
thousands of dollars and never pay back.

406
00:25:19,992 --> 00:25:23,016
Spare me the lecture. / But "sorry" 
doesn't cover nearly killing a patient

407
00:25:23,016 --> 00:25:26,044
because you're so distracted and tired
that all you think about is gambling.

408
00:25:26,044 --> 00:25:28,037
This has nothing to do with the cards.

409
00:25:28,037 --> 00:25:30,205
- You have a problem.
- That's crap.

410
00:25:30,205 --> 00:25:32,837
Admit it. / I need sleep.
I worked two shifts.

411
00:25:32,837 --> 00:25:36,043
- Stop lying.
- He's right.

412
00:25:37,294 --> 00:25:41,521
- What?
- Mom knows it, too.

413
00:25:41,521 --> 00:25:44,778
You lie about everything now.

414
00:25:44,778 --> 00:25:48,269
Now you're both lecturing me?

415
00:25:48,269 --> 00:25:51,705
- What the hell is this?
- End of the line, Grant.

416
00:25:51,705 --> 00:25:54,545
You're coming with me.

417
00:26:02,658 --> 00:26:05,119
End of innocence, huh?

418
00:26:06,180 --> 00:26:07,789
You could say.

419
00:26:07,789 --> 00:26:10,434
Where was Dr. Garvey taking your dad?

420
00:26:10,434 --> 00:26:12,848
I never asked.

421
00:26:18,301 --> 00:26:22,178
Something you forgot to tell us, 
Dr. Garvey? /  I don't think so.

422
00:26:22,178 --> 00:26:24,723
You hauled Grant out of the ER, 
day he died.

423
00:26:24,723 --> 00:26:27,258
- Makes you last-to-see.
- And maybe the shooter.

424
00:26:27,258 --> 00:26:29,971
- I didn't shoot Grant.
- You did something you tried to hide.

425
00:26:29,971 --> 00:26:32,888
Yeah. I covered for Grant
when he almost killed a patient.

426
00:26:32,888 --> 00:26:34,333
The hospital could have been sued.

427
00:26:34,333 --> 00:26:37,815
Fact remains, you're
the last guy seen with Grant.

428
00:26:37,815 --> 00:26:40,550
You had it bad for his wife,
and you were jealous of him at work.

429
00:26:40,550 --> 00:26:44,997
Not at that point.  I wasn't jealous 
of him in any way. / No?

430
00:26:44,997 --> 00:26:48,783
I pitied him.
And, yes, I interfered.

431
00:26:48,783 --> 00:26:51,698
I did it for her.

432
00:26:51,698 --> 00:26:54,272
- Anne.
- You did what?

433
00:26:54,272 --> 00:26:58,523
I took him to a gambler's anonymous 
meeting...basement of saint Michael's.

434
00:26:58,523 --> 00:27:00,980
- He sit still for that?
- Far as I know.

435
00:27:00,980 --> 00:27:03,419
I stayed a few minutes,
but I was working.

436
00:27:03,419 --> 00:27:05,882
Anyone see you leave the meeting?

437
00:27:05,882 --> 00:27:10,392
Yeah. That mutt Cy Tisdale.

438
00:27:20,988 --> 00:27:24,185
Those food stamps you're playing for?

439
00:27:27,767 --> 00:27:29,285
Lot of bazooms.

440
00:27:29,285 --> 00:27:32,241
Got some new information, Cy.

441
00:27:34,538 --> 00:27:37,058
What now?

442
00:27:38,733 --> 00:27:42,753
Witness put you and Grant at a gambler's 
anonymous meeting the day of the murder.

443
00:27:42,753 --> 00:27:46,135
Want to tell us why you 
failed to mention that? / Not really. No.

444
00:27:46,135 --> 00:27:48,228
Went to talk to your old pal, Skinny.

445
00:27:48,228 --> 00:27:51,447
- See about that alibi of yours.
- Oh, yeah? How's he doing?

446
00:27:51,447 --> 00:27:53,566
- Not so good.
- Been dead a decade.

447
00:27:53,566 --> 00:27:55,367
But that's no surprise to you, is it?

448
00:27:55,367 --> 00:27:58,265
I got feelings, you know.

449
00:27:58,265 --> 00:28:00,326
- That's hurtful.
- Quit bluffing, Cy.

450
00:28:00,326 --> 00:28:03,826
Tell us what happened
to Dr. Bowen that day.

451
00:28:05,709 --> 00:28:09,526
- The birds is what happened.
- Birds?

452
00:28:09,526 --> 00:28:13,792
Pigeons, to be exact.

453
00:28:14,712 --> 00:28:17,003
I almost killed someone today,

454
00:28:17,003 --> 00:28:20,049
right in front of my son.

455
00:28:20,049 --> 00:28:22,767
And now he hates me.

456
00:28:22,767 --> 00:28:24,844
And it's not even an hour later,

457
00:28:24,844 --> 00:28:29,810
and all I can think about
is how to get to a game.

458
00:28:29,810 --> 00:28:36,554
I've lost my wife, my son, my job.

459
00:28:36,554 --> 00:28:41,007
But I keep thinking my luck will turn.

460
00:28:41,007 --> 00:28:44,692
That's the beauty of chance.

461
00:28:44,692 --> 00:28:49,995
The beauty I couldn't resist.
I'll try, though.

462
00:28:49,995 --> 00:28:55,325
Try accepting I'm going out a loser.

463
00:29:01,964 --> 00:29:04,168
What the hell are you doing here?

464
00:29:04,168 --> 00:29:06,276
- I come here sometimes.
- To quit?

465
00:29:06,276 --> 00:29:10,697
To remind myself
why I don't want to quit.

466
00:29:10,697 --> 00:29:12,811
Look at these sad sacks.

467
00:29:12,811 --> 00:29:16,557
Put a c-note in any of their hands, 
they'd be out the door.

468
00:29:16,557 --> 00:29:19,289
Not me. Not anymore.

469
00:29:19,289 --> 00:29:21,864
- Had a dream last night, doc.
- Oh, yeah?

470
00:29:21,864 --> 00:29:26,028
Had the ten, jack, queen 
and king of spades. And the river...

471
00:29:26,028 --> 00:29:29,781
- it dropped me the ace of spades.
- A royal flush.

472
00:29:29,781 --> 00:29:33,725
I think it's a premonition
that our luck's about to change.

473
00:29:33,725 --> 00:29:36,432
That's your dream, Cy.

474
00:29:36,432 --> 00:29:38,506
Mine are all nightmares.

475
00:29:38,506 --> 00:29:41,916
Look at that, would you?

476
00:29:41,916 --> 00:29:47,628
A buck says the gray flies off first.

477
00:29:47,628 --> 00:29:52,154
- I'm quitting, Cy.
- Tell you what.

478
00:29:52,154 --> 00:29:57,513
You take the gray,
I'll take speckles.

479
00:30:03,391 --> 00:30:08,260
- I'll take speckles.
- That's the spirit.

480
